My research integrates thermodynamics, materials degradation, tribology, manufacturing, and intelligent monitoring to develop practical methods for assessing damage, predicting failure, and improving process quality.

## Research Areas

### Degradation Entropy Generation

Development and application of entropy-based methods for quantifying degradation, identifying failure thresholds, and predicting remaining useful life in engineering systems.

### Hydrogen Embrittlement

Thermodynamic assessment of hydrogen-assisted degradation in steels and stainless steels using mechanical testing, electrochemical charging, microscopy, and entropy-based damage parameters.

### Tribology and Lubrication

Investigation of friction, wear, lubricant degradation, grease remaining useful life, and condition monitoring in rotating machinery.

### Molecular Dynamics

Atomistic simulation of deformation, dislocation evolution, damage accumulation, and entropy generation in metallic materials under different strain rates and length scales.

### Food-Process Monitoring

Development of non-invasive methods for monitoring mixing, consistency, rheology, and product quality using electrical, mechanical, and thermodynamic process signals.

### Corrosion and Additive Manufacturing

Evaluation of corrosion-induced degradation, porosity, mechanical-property retention, and entropy generation in conventionally manufactured and additively manufactured materials.

### Battery Health Monitoring

Development of thermodynamic and data-driven approaches for battery degradation assessment, state-of-health estimation, and remaining discharge prediction.

### Intelligent Manufacturing

Integration of sensors, machine learning, process analytics, and real-time monitoring for quality prediction and manufacturing decision support.
